The '''Priority Enforcement Program''' ('''PEP''') is a program by the [[U.S. Department of Homeland Security]] with two primary components. First, it provides an updated official list of enforcement priorities and guidance to [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] on how to implement those prioties. Second, it provides new rules on how to use the cooperation of state and local law enforcement, replacing the rules of [[Secure Communities and administrative immigration policies|Secure Communities]].<ref name=ice-pep>{{cite web|url = https://www.ice.gov/pep|title = Priority Enforcement Program|publisher = [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]]|accessdate = June 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=migrationpolicy>{{cite web|url = http://www.migrationpolicy.org/research/understanding-potential-impact-executive-action-immigration-enforcement|title = Understanding the Potential Impact of Executive Action on Immigration Enforcement|date = July 1, 2015|last = Rosenblum|first = Marc|accessdate = June 22, 2016|publisher = [[Migration Policy Institute]]}}</ref><ref name=ilrc>{{cite web|url = http://www.ilrc.org/files/documents/life_under_pepcomm.pdf|title = Life under "PEP-Comm"|publisher = Immigrant Legal Resource Center|accessdate = June 24, 2016}}</ref> It was based on a memo by [[U.S. Department of Homeland Security]] Secretary [[Jeh Johnson]] on November 20, 2014, issued as part of President Barack Obama's announcement of a number of executive changes surrounding immigration.<ref name=johnson-pep-memo>{{cite web|url = https://www.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/publications/14_1120_memo_prosecutorial_discretion.pdf|title = Policies for the Apprehension, Detention and Removal of Undocumented Immigrants|date = November 20, 2014|accessdate = June 20, 2016|publisher = [[U.S. Department of Homeland SEcurity]]|last = Johnson|first = Jeh Charles|authorlink = Jeh Johnson}}</ref><ref name=migrationpolicy/> The official rollout of the program started on July 2, 2015.<ref name=numbers